context: A later literary standard, dating from the later <a2_0>10th<a2_0/> century, arose under the influence of <a1_0><b7_0>Bishop Æthelwold of Winchester<a1_0/>,<b7_0/> and was followed by such writers as the prolific <a0_0><b8_0>Ælfric of Eynsham<b8_0/><a0_0/> ("the Grammarian"). This form of the language is known as the <b5_0>"Winchester standard",<b5_0/> or more commonly as <a3_0><b6_0>Late West Saxon<a3_0/>.<b6_0/> It is considered to represent the "classical" form of Old English. It retained its position of prestige until the time of <a4_0>the Norman Conquest<a4_0/>, after which English ceased for a time to be of importance as a literary language.
